00:00:12,081 --> 00:00:15,011
Grow the attitude of, you are important.

7
00:00:15,011 --> 00:00:16,131
3.

8
00:00:16,321 --> 00:00:19,250
Grow the attitude of, service first.

9
00:00:20,879 --> 00:00:23,250
Now, let's see how.

10
00:00:23,521 --> 00:00:29,331
Years ago, when I was a college sophomore, I enrolled in an American history class.

11
00:00:29,600 --> 00:00:34,771
I remember the class vividly, not because I learned much about American history,

12
00:00:34,879 --> 00:00:40,691
but because, in an unusual way, I learned this basic principle of successful living.

13
00:00:40,800 --> 00:00:45,091
To activate others, you must first activate yourself.

14
00:00:45,680 --> 00:00:51,091
The history class was very large, and it was held in a fan-shaped auditorium.

15
00:00:51,201 --> 00:00:58,290
The professor, who was a middle-aged fellow and apparently well-educated, was nevertheless pathetically dull.

16
00:00:58,560 --> 00:01:07,331
Rather than interpret history as an alive, fascinating subject, the professor merely cited one dead fact after another.

17
00:01:07,521 --> 00:01:13,971
It was a frightful wonder how he could possibly make such an interesting subject so terribly dull.

18
00:01:14,081 --> 00:01:15,170
But he did.

19
00:01:15,761 --> 00:01:20,050
You can imagine the effect the professor's boredom had on the students.

20
00:01:20,321 --> 00:01:31,331
Talking and sleeping got so out of hand that the professor had two assistants patrol the aisles to break up student conversations and wake up those who had dozed off.

21
00:01:31,841 --> 00:01:36,850
Occasionally, the professor would stop and, shaking his finger at the class, would say,

22
00:01:37,120 --> 00:01:40,850
I'm warning you, you've got to pay attention to what I say.

23
00:01:41,040 --> 00:01:44,610
You've got to stop this talking, and that's all there is to it.

24
00:01:45,201 --> 00:01:50,451
This, of course, made little impression on his students, many of whom, as veterans,

25
00:01:50,480 --> 00:01:57,011
had gambled their lives only months before, had made history on islands and in bombers.

26
00:01:57,761 --> 00:02:04,771
As I sat there watching this potentially great, wonderful experience turn into a disgusting farce,

27
00:02:04,961 --> 00:02:11,571
I found myself wrestling with the question, why are the students ignoring what the professor has to say?

28
00:02:12,081 --> 00:02:13,651
The answer came.

